{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17494312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17494312"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1328"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17494328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17494328"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:40:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:40:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1328"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1328"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.02,0.25,0.02,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47355"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1328"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32084"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"947"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45566"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47355"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a two-month history of recurrent right upper quadrant pain. The practitioner diagnoses biliary colic and an ultrasound confirms the presence of gallstones. The practitioner suggests that the patient will need prompt attention as these episodes of biliary colic are occurring most days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient requests referral to a particular surgeon whose website she has been studying. In it, the surgeon claims that they perform laparoscopic cholecystectomies using a technique that uses smaller instruments with fewer keyholes. The General Practitioner is aware that this technique is not routinely used due to a higher rate of complications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Comply with the patient\u0027s wishes to respect patient autonomy","Refer the surgeon to the medical board","Call the surgeon and clarify your concerns before offering the referral","Refer the patient to the Emergency Department","Explain your concerns to the patient and refer to a different surgeon"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EReferral of a patient to another medical professional is an integral part of medical practice. The Medical Board of Australia\u2019s code of conduct states that \u201cGood Medical Practice involves taking reasonable steps to ensure that the person to whom you delegate, refer or handover has the qualifications, experience, knowledge and skills to provide the care required.\u201d Additionally, the referring practitioner should \u201cTake steps to protect patients from risk posed by a colleague\u2019s conduct, practice or ill health.\u201d\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESo in this particular scenario, \u003Cstrong\u003Eexplain your concerns to the patient and refer to a different surgeon\u003C/strong\u003E may be in the patient\u2019s best interest. Whilst the practitioner might have their concerns about this particular surgeon, they must not disparage that individual to the patient. At the same time, the practitioner must tactfully explain to the patient why they cannot comply with the patient\u0027s specific request and provide an alternative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplying with the patient\u0027s wishes\u003C/strong\u003E without addressing the potential risks associated with the surgeon\u0027s technique would not be in the best interest of the patient and could lead to a negative outcome for the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring the surgeon to the medical board\u003C/strong\u003E may be obligatory if there is evidence of malpractice or significant risk, but it does not address the immediate need for the patient\u0027s surgical care nor is it clear that there is adequate evidence to report.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalling the surgeon\u003C/strong\u003E to clarify concerns is a reasonable step, but it does not directly address the patient\u0027s immediate need for a safe and effective surgical referral.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring the patient to the Emergency Department\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this context as the patient requires elective surgical management rather than emergency care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Medical Board of Australia\u2019s code of conduct outlines the responsibilities of clinicians when providing referrals to other healthcare practitioners."],"references":["Good medical practice: A code of conduct for doctors in Australia. In: Medical Board of Australia [online]. 2014. Available at: www.medicalboard.gov.au/Codes-Guidelines-Policies/Code-of-conduct.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32084"}},"questio